<BaseLayout title="About | Arvind Puthucode" pageClass="garden-theme">
  <h1>About</h1>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>Arvind Puthucode</h2>
    <p>
      Product-minded engineer and founder building ScoutFox, a product for
      catching important web changes before they become obvious.
    </p>

    <p>
      I like work where the boundaries are messy: talking to users, figuring out
      what matters, building the backend, shipping the product, and improving it
      when reality disagrees with the first version.
    </p>

    <p>
      I started my career as an engineer working on augmented analytics systems
      and large-scale data pipelines. Over time I became fascinated by a
      broader question: how do people notice the signals that actually matter
      for decisions?
    </p>

    <p>
      The internet produces enormous amounts of information every day: new
      research, product launches, regulatory changes, and market shifts. Most
      of these signals appear quietly across scattered sources long before they
      become obvious.
    </p>

    <p>Humans miss them constantly.</p>

    <p>
      That curiosity led me to build before I had the final answer. I first
      built an edtech app for Socratic learning. It taught me that learning
      products often require changing human psychology, and edtech markets are
      highly personal and heavily commoditized.
    </p>

    <p>
      I wanted to work on a harder systems problem that felt less mundane, so I
      moved to a second project: SignalNotNoise, a brand focused on
      understanding influencer marketing more deeply.
    </p>

    <p>
      That effort exposed the bigger question underneath all campaigns: what
      are the right signals to track for a specific goal? That question became
      the foundation for ScoutFox.
    </p>

    <p>
      In October 2025, I left my role to explore this direction more deeply
      through founder residencies and independent experiments.
    </p>

    <p>
      During the Lossfunk residency (Jan-Feb 2026), I started building
      ScoutFox, a system that monitors the web intelligently, builds baselines
      around entities and relationships, and surfaces signals users should not
      miss.
    </p>

    <p>
      ScoutFox later won the OSS4AI February Hackathon and is currently being
      developed through the TinyFish accelerator program. It is now used in
      work around journalism, venture, research, and competitive
      intelligence, including users at Business Today and Analytics India
      Magazine.
    </p>

    <p>
      My long-term focus is to build systems that surface the signals humans need
      to make better decisions. ScoutFox is the strongest evidence of how I work:
      ambiguous problem, real users, shipped product, and constant iteration
      when quality is not yet good enough.
    </p>

    <p>
      Outside of startups, I enjoy exploring unusual questions across science,
      intelligence systems, and technology.
    </p>
  </section>

